I guess, from two perspectives. First of all, I'm a diehard R fan, so I'm going to say,

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:18.199
no, you should be getting, if standardization is your goal,

00:22:18.199 --> 00:22:23.239
get them all to use R. I realize that may not be practical, and that's definitely

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:34.199
me being a big booster of R. I think you have to do whatever makes sense for your team.

00:22:34.199 --> 00:22:41.479
So I certainly can say that within the Tidyverse team, for example, we do really try to standardize

00:22:41.479 --> 00:22:48.680
our practices for doing certain things and enshrine that in tools because it removes decision

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:54.599
fatigue. It creates consistency that when you need to go drop in on somebody else's project,

00:22:54.599 --> 00:23:00.199
you know where the bathroom is. You don't walk in and you're like, what the heck is going on here?

00:23:00.199 --> 00:23:07.719
So I think having at least deliberate choices about when we're consistent and when we allow

00:23:07.719 --> 00:23:13.640
people to follow their heart does make a lot of sense. And then I definitely am not the person

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:21.400
to talk to about putting models in production. I'm going to refer that to Julia Silgi or

00:23:22.199 --> 00:23:26.760
other people. I'm definitely like, that's outside of my wheelhouse.

00:23:28.119 --> 00:23:33.239
Yeah, that's fine. I'm proficient with both R and Python, but you're saying either one of the

00:23:33.239 --> 00:23:38.680
other is good, right? Regardless of the language. I think so. And then I think, you know, it's going

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:45.560
to depend on your group whether you want to sort of standardize on one or the other. Certainly,

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:53.560
I would say that Posit is all in on building a tooling ecosystem that should make it very easy

00:23:53.640 --> 00:23:58.040
for individual people or individual teams to use a lot of both.

00:24:02.520 --> 00:24:05.800
Thank you. Thank you. Thank you so much for the great question, Jacob.

00:24:07.079 --> 00:24:14.680
I saw one from Sam and Sam had an asterisk, which in case anybody doesn't know, you can always put

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:19.160
an asterisk in your question. That's sort of a little unspoken rule we have here if you want

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:25.000
me to ask it for you. And Sam asks, how do you navigate the law of the instrument,

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:30.439
law of the instrument in quotations here, when working with emerging tools like LLMs? I've

00:24:30.439 --> 00:24:36.199
noticed parallels with Shiny where it sometimes gets applied to problems that it might not be

00:24:36.199 --> 00:24:42.760
best suited for. So how do you balance enthusiasm for new tools with thoughtful tool selection?

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:47.880
All right. I have to confess, I don't know what the law of the instrument is. If so,

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:51.880
if anyone... Neither do I. Somebody put that in the chat for us. Sam, help us out.

00:24:51.880 --> 00:25:00.040
Yeah. I'll vamp for a bit, but maybe someone can supply that. Like, I guess my main response to

00:25:00.040 --> 00:25:08.040
this is I think it, I think LLMs are like a chainsaw. Like, it really is very easy to like,

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:14.599
open an artery and just like, to use it either on something that you shouldn't,

00:25:14.599 --> 00:25:19.719
or I'm less worried about that, but to like, trust it too much. Yeah. Do we have an answer

00:25:19.719 --> 00:25:23.880
that might help? We do. It's the, when you have a hammer, everything looks like a nail.

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:37.880
Oh, okay. Okay. Okay. So I will just say that I try to be just super bossy with LLMs,

00:25:37.959 --> 00:25:48.680
and very critical of their output. So I've only done something that I would say was vibe-coded

00:25:49.479 --> 00:25:58.839
once. So I much more ask very targeted questions, and I'm pretty willing to be like,

00:25:58.839 --> 00:26:03.479
are you sure? Or like, this doesn't make sense to me. Or just start the conversation over if

00:26:03.479 --> 00:26:12.760
we've gotten to some local minimum, like, of quality. So I don't know. That's my main answer

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:19.640
is they are super helpful, but yeah, sometimes it's also true that you need to just back out

00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:25.560
and think about the problem yourself. But I think if you use LLMs in that way, like you really think

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:31.400
about your prompt, you really think about the context, and you really critique each answer,

00:26:32.199 --> 00:26:40.760
they end up acting like a giant rubber duck. And so, and that can be very healthy, because it's

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:48.520
making you articulate, this is my problem. These are the constraints. I want it to look consistent

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:55.000
with this code base. I'm worried about building a very inefficient solution or something like that.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:00.760
But like forcing you to say those things actually forces you to think those things. So I think

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:08.439
certain types of habits in your LLM use can actually force you to refine your own thinking,

00:27:08.439 --> 00:27:13.160
whereas before you might have just started coding, right? So I think there are ways

00:27:13.719 --> 00:27:18.040
to use them that keep your brain like plugged in.

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:24.920
I agree. Kylie in the chat says, I use an LLM as a critical colleague.

00:27:25.880 --> 00:27:30.040
Yeah. And I like that a lot. And somebody else says that it's a non-critical rubber duck.

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:31.319
Or a colleague to critique.

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:33.719
Yeah. Oh, gosh, well.

00:27:33.719 --> 00:27:39.880
Also, yeah. I'm like, are you sure? Or I'm like, I don't like the way you did such and such,

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:45.239
fix that. And you know, just you can be bossy in ways that you would not be with an actual colleague.

00:27:45.959 --> 00:27:49.079
Yeah. And a lot of times it's not going to listen to you anyway.

00:27:49.079 --> 00:27:49.079


00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:50.140
True.

