00:28:24.119 --> 00:28:28.680
So do you have any general advice for those data scientists who find themselves

00:28:28.680 --> 00:28:32.680
wanting to maybe branch out more into software engineering, but don't have the formal training?

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:38.280
Well, that definitely describes me, not having formal training.

00:28:38.599 --> 00:28:47.079
And so I think that the steps and it will, yeah, I have, I actually had a segment in a talk

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:55.719
once that showed that like cake fails photo, right, of someone making like a beautiful cake

00:28:55.719 --> 00:29:00.359
that looked like a hedgehog in a woodland, right. And then there was, you know, and here's my

00:29:00.359 --> 00:29:05.239
version and it's just this like brown blob with like pretzel sticks sticking out of it, you know.

00:29:05.479 --> 00:29:13.560
And the theme of that is this phrase that like your taste develops much faster than your ability.

00:29:14.359 --> 00:29:17.160
So once you decide like, hey, I'm really into software development,

00:29:17.719 --> 00:29:22.280
then you start looking at your own code and you're like, God, that's just so awful.

00:29:23.079 --> 00:29:27.400
And so then how do you like start making forward progress again?

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:30.760
So I definitely went through this. I think I continue to go through this.

00:29:30.839 --> 00:29:36.439
So reading, really reading the code of people whose work you respect

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:41.719
is the number one thing that changed how I wrote code.

00:29:43.400 --> 00:29:50.680
Number one, so like actually reading a lot of source code written by someone who you admire.

00:29:53.479 --> 00:29:59.319
It has helped, of course, a lot. Like once I joined RStudio and I was part of it,

00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:08.040
I was part of the Tidyverse team, getting code review from people whose code you admire

00:30:08.040 --> 00:30:17.400
and just being able to take the feedback without feeling crushed or whatever.

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:21.079
Of course, that, you know, highly benefits from having,

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:26.680
you know, well-wishing, polite people to do that.

00:30:27.319 --> 00:30:33.400
So reading other people's code, really inviting people, if you can, to review your code.

00:30:35.719 --> 00:30:40.680
Another early thing I did was, you know, just starting to write packages,

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:46.359
just like forcing myself to do it, even though I was kind of embarrassed by some of the internals.

00:30:47.160 --> 00:30:54.839
But like pushing some small project to completion instead of getting stuck on,

00:30:54.839 --> 00:30:58.359
oh, this isn't perfect, this isn't right. But I'm like, well, it behaves right.

00:30:58.359 --> 00:31:02.119
I think what's inside is kind of gross in many ways, but it has the correct behavior.

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:06.920
And slowly leveling up the internals, maybe by starting all over.

00:31:09.719 --> 00:31:15.319
And often finding those little projects that you can just force yourself to complete is much easier

00:31:16.199 --> 00:31:19.319
if you allow yourself to do something kind of recreational.

00:31:19.880 --> 00:31:28.680
Because it feels like the stakes are lower and it feels less awful to make mistakes or to feel like,

00:31:28.680 --> 00:31:36.359
oh, the internals are kind of gross. But if it's a package, you know, to analyze your Spotify list,

00:31:36.359 --> 00:31:41.160
like, I mean, the stakes are low anyway, so that's fine. But so sometimes finding

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:45.800
a project that's like interesting enough to you personally that you want to do it,

00:31:45.800 --> 00:31:52.280
but it's also silly enough that it's fine if it's not perfect, can be very good for getting unblocked.

00:31:56.920 --> 00:31:59.959
Yeah, and then like hanging out in places where people talk about code,

00:31:59.959 --> 00:32:06.280
like RStats Twitter was good for that. But I think you can find Slack communities for that,

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:13.319
following certain hashtags, following the GitHub repositories of packages you care about,

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:18.599
and like really listening to what do people talk about? What do pull request reviews look like?

00:32:18.599 --> 00:32:25.239
There's a lot of people who work in the open, and you can lurk in lots of situations where

00:32:25.239 --> 00:32:30.760
sort of people you admire are talking in detail about code and refining things and

00:32:31.400 --> 00:32:35.400
working out disagreements and can sort of learn a lot just by watching that happen,

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:39.959
even if you don't work on that team or whatever. Those are a few ideas.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:45.719
Those are great ideas. I encourage everybody, actually, if you ever feel intimidated about

00:32:45.719 --> 00:32:51.640
the people who build the tools that you use, like go check out GitHub issues on like-

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:52.599
Watch them work.

00:32:52.599 --> 00:32:57.319
Dplyr. Yeah, yeah. Go look at Hadley trying to figure out the name for purr,

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:01.400
like suggesting a bunch of things that were not purr that were wild.

00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:08.680
They work out loud and in the open. There's no secrets there, so go check those out.

