Lady, can you ask this for me? Awesome. The question is, why should I learn Positron

00:33:39.180 --> 00:33:40.380
instead of VS Code?

00:33:42.939 --> 00:33:51.180
Oh, because if you like having an interactive REPL right there, for example, like so the R

00:33:51.180 --> 00:33:57.260
console that you can send code to, I guess this is possible in VS Code, but involves like a lot

00:33:57.260 --> 00:34:05.900
more fragile setup on your part. So having that be a just basic core feature of the IDE for a

00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:13.020
practicing data scientist who uses R or Python or R and Python, I think that's huge. Like the way

00:34:13.020 --> 00:34:29.100
the console is feature one in Positron, then I think also after that comes things like the

00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:39.100
environments pane, the plots pane, like all the sort of data science specific tooling that's just

00:34:39.899 --> 00:34:44.620
the core product as opposed to things you might need to sort of configure and get working together

00:34:44.620 --> 00:34:50.540
on one day and then sort of actively maintain to keep them all playing nicely together. I think

00:34:50.540 --> 00:35:01.979
those are the main reasons for Positron over VS Code. My colleague Davis is here, who was also

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:07.260
seconded to the Positron team with me. Do you have anything else that you think?

00:35:09.100 --> 00:35:13.020
We should add. Did you mention the data explorer? Did I hear that?

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:18.860
I was just going to say data explorer. Oh, okay. Yeah. So having, you know,

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:24.379
once you've got a data frame in one of your R or Python sessions and you have a way to like

00:35:24.379 --> 00:35:29.820
fling it into this data explorer through different gestures and look at it like it's a spreadsheet,

00:35:30.139 --> 00:35:39.340
um, which can be super handy. You know, the way I use it is when what few data science tasks I

00:35:39.340 --> 00:35:44.699
still do is frequently I need that kind of tangibility to write my code or to figure out

00:35:44.699 --> 00:35:50.860
why my data wrangling code isn't working and can use that sort of spreadsheet to like stare at the

00:35:50.860 --> 00:35:57.020
data or like get a few rows at the top that I feel like are causing me problems to better create my

00:35:57.020 --> 00:36:04.060
code. Yeah. And I feel like each of those elements is like sort of possible in VS Code,

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:11.260
but it's like a lot more janky and it's a lot more on you to get individual extensions or things

00:36:11.260 --> 00:36:20.300
working together. But yeah, when I see these questions, when Positron is discussed in places

00:36:20.300 --> 00:36:25.020
I'm like, Jess, why didn't you just use VS Code? I'm like, are you serious? That's like my actual

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:29.580
response to that because I'm like, it is so different. So it usually tells me like this

00:36:29.580 --> 00:36:36.780
person doesn't do a ton of data science or they're like completely notebook focused

00:36:37.820 --> 00:36:42.540
and they're getting all that stuff sort of from notebooks and they don't understand,

00:36:42.540 --> 00:36:48.060
they don't know what they don't know, is my reaction when I see comments like that. I'm like,

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:56.060
that tells me that you've never worked in this way and experienced how awesome it is.

00:36:56.060 --> 00:37:00.540
So that's like, you know, that could be a slightly obnoxious answer, but I'm always

00:37:00.540 --> 00:37:05.100
like actually really surprised by that. We don't feel like you are obnoxious,

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:11.020
Rodrigo. Okay. We really love you asking. No, my answer might be obnoxious, but I do think it's,

00:37:11.979 --> 00:37:18.699
it's a good question though. It comes from, and this is totally me and I could be

00:37:20.060 --> 00:37:25.419
undereducated about it, but I think it comes from like, I think notebooks are so popular in Python

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:32.379
partially because there wasn't like an RStudio type thing, but people still wanted the interactivity

00:37:32.379 --> 00:37:38.300
and so that problem got solved in a different way, but I still think the way we do it in R

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:46.379
and RStudio is extremely relevant to Python and it's pretty different from what you can do in VS

00:37:46.379 --> 00:37:52.300
Code or you can, you can do it better in Positron than in VS Code, I think. Yeah. And a lot of times

00:37:52.300 --> 00:37:57.419
some of the people that I've talked to who asked this question already have a really, really

00:37:57.419 --> 00:38:02.540
customized VS Code setup and they're, they're like, oh, well you can do that in VS Code with

00:38:02.540 --> 00:38:09.100
an extension and they're just kind of not thinking that, oh, I've spent the past five or six years

00:38:09.100 --> 00:38:14.459
customizing my VS Code. Rigging those. Yeah. And really rigging it to work for me. Yeah. Whereas

00:38:14.459 --> 00:38:18.699
with Positron, there might be some differences, but it's kind of right out of the box. And one

00:38:18.699 --> 00:38:25.580
thing that as an educator, I have really enjoyed is I can get someone set up in Positron fairly

00:38:25.580 --> 00:38:30.459
quickly and they have all the same functionality out of the box that I do. I don't have to like

00:38:30.459 --> 00:38:34.939
teach them how to go search for the extensions that are going to specifically solve their

00:38:34.939 --> 00:38:40.939
niche problems. Everything is just there for them. It's amazing. Yeah. So if someone has crafted

00:38:41.659 --> 00:38:47.179
a system for themselves over the years, you know, the value proposition might be lower,

00:38:47.899 --> 00:38:51.580
but there's a whole bunch of people for whom it is super compelling.

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:57.100
I agree. All right. Well, let's move on. Rodrigo, thank you so much for asking that

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:01.899
brilliant question that we were all sort of wondering as well. And I saw a question from

00:39:01.899 --> 00:39:07.340
Dami, my buddy, Dami. Dami, are you available to ask your question live? Of course.

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:15.820
All right. Let's do it. It was one about happy Git and the GitHub user for R, I think.

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:21.899
Oh, wait, let me, how do you find questions? Okay. I'm going to highlight your question. So

00:39:21.899 --> 00:39:24.780
it's going to pop up to the top and I will also stick it in the chat.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:35.179
So Jenny, I would just ask a question. Happy Git is like one of the things that saved me the

00:39:35.179 --> 00:39:40.780
most when I was in grad school. Like I read it religiously. I gave it to everyone. I printed it

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:46.780
out. And I'm always like amazed how much I come back to it, like even like five years from now.

00:39:47.739 --> 00:39:53.500
Can you tell me like how you write like technical documents? Like how do you like view the audience?

00:39:53.500 --> 00:39:58.300
Like do you, how do you gauge the skill levels? And do you have any tips on how to like, you know,

00:39:58.300 --> 00:40:05.020
talk about these kinds of really technical questions or technical skills to like non-technical

00:40:05.020 --> 00:40:13.179
audiences? Oh, one like principle that like definitely comes to mind for me is

00:40:13.659 --> 00:40:18.699
if there's something I needed to know to work, it needs to be in the talk or the book or the

00:40:18.699 --> 00:40:23.739
post or the docs. And if there's something I have never needed to know, it does not need to be there.

00:40:26.300 --> 00:40:33.820
And that's like super clarifying because I think often when you write docs or books or articles or

00:40:33.820 --> 00:40:39.739
whatever, it's so easy to be like, you pull way back and you're like, let's start at the very

00:40:39.739 --> 00:40:45.179
beginning. And you go off and like do research on things that like you've never actually needed

00:40:45.179 --> 00:40:49.020
to know. And like, if you're writing, you know, the definitive account of something,

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:52.860
you do need to do that. But most people don't want to read the definitive account of things.

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:58.060
And so I kind of feel like if there's something that you've never needed to know, let's say about

00:40:58.060 --> 00:41:04.699
Git, since that's what we're talking about, and you operate like at a pretty high level in Git for

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:10.780
10 years, it's pretty safe that you don't need to mention it now, or at least you have the permission

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:18.459
to not mention it now. And likewise, there's often gross little moves that you need to make that

00:41:18.459 --> 00:41:25.979
actually help in your daily life, but they feel like too small a detail to mention, or it's

00:41:25.979 --> 00:41:32.379
embarrassing that you do this. And then I'm like, no, if it's like some move that you need to make,

00:41:32.379 --> 00:41:37.340
if it's like some move that you need to make on a regular basis, even if it feels inelegant,

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:42.620
you should probably write about it, because it's friction that actual people do encounter.

00:41:43.739 --> 00:41:49.659
So letting your own experience of a tool, giving yourself permission to like actually

00:41:49.659 --> 00:41:56.459
write about it that way. So a lot of what's in HappyGit, like the way the website came about is

00:41:57.419 --> 00:42:05.500
back in my prof days, we would drag classes of 100 or more people every semester through the

00:42:05.500 --> 00:42:12.300
fun experience of getting Git and GitHub set up. And so we ended up with this just like battle-tested

00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:19.580
set of instructions and a very good list of like problems that people have. And then we turned

00:42:19.659 --> 00:42:25.340
that just sort of collective, like super painfully gained wisdom into that resource.

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:32.459
And then I think another phrase that's really helpful comes from Greg Wilson of Software

00:42:32.459 --> 00:42:39.899
Carpentry, which is never let truth get in the way of clarity. Like letting yourself write things

00:42:39.899 --> 00:42:45.979
sometimes that are not like absolutely, totally, completely pedantically true, but it's like,

00:42:46.620 --> 00:42:52.939
it's the truth that actually matters. That can also be very freeing to write things that are like,

00:42:53.820 --> 00:42:58.060
reasonably short, readable, and will work for most people most of the time,

00:42:58.060 --> 00:43:04.219
but, you know, is glossing over some technicality or something like that. So those are some

00:43:05.899 --> 00:43:10.139
principles that I think about when I'm like, how should I write about this? I sort of

00:43:11.179 --> 00:43:12.540
think about those sorts of things.

00:43:13.340 --> 00:43:19.500
Thank you. Great question, Dami. We have all really benefited from all of Jenny's technical

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:25.260
writing for audiences, technical and not, because a lot of us educators are also using that to teach

