that you don't see it. And it just feels like so overwhelming sometimes. So, could you maybe speak

00:48:27.419 --> 00:48:33.820
to like the value that you see in it and like ways that you can maybe kind of clear that mental

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:41.979
hurdle and feel like you're going to get some value from it? Well, I highly recommend doing

00:48:42.060 --> 00:48:49.979
like a speed run to some micro package that fully works as one function. But it has a website.

00:48:50.620 --> 00:48:58.379
That function is tested. Like that is a vastly better way to move forward than writing tons

00:48:58.379 --> 00:49:03.340
and tons of R code. You know, I've written 20 functions and they all live in like something.r

00:49:03.340 --> 00:49:06.780
and I source them. I'm going to turn that into a pack. Well, actually, you could turn that into

00:49:06.780 --> 00:49:13.580
a package. But I would still recommend create the package, bring one function in, and get it

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:21.020
documented, tested, create the website, like get the whole little ecosystem working, and then

00:49:21.659 --> 00:49:26.780
port your second function over. And this is for a variety of reasons. But first of all,

00:49:26.780 --> 00:49:34.699
it's like super motivating. Like the first time you see a help topic that you wrote in the help

00:49:34.699 --> 00:49:40.060
pane, that feels so great. Like that's like the package development equivalent of making your

00:49:40.060 --> 00:49:48.219
first ggplot. It feels tremendous. And then the first time you see that on the web, as part of

00:49:48.219 --> 00:49:55.820
your packages, like package down site, also super motivating. Okay, so like, whereas if you just like

00:49:55.820 --> 00:50:00.219
hone one function over and over and over again, that just feels like that's what you've always

00:50:00.219 --> 00:50:09.820
been doing. So getting the whole little thing working is very motivating. And also, you're going

00:50:09.820 --> 00:50:16.699
to make mistakes along the way. And if you're, if you're getting the documentation to work, you're

00:50:16.699 --> 00:50:21.899
running our command check, you're making the website, you're pushing, you catch those little

00:50:21.899 --> 00:50:28.620
mistakes like right away. And since you've only changed like four lines of code in the past hour,

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:33.899
it's like pretty clear where you made your mistake, and you can solve them. So and then you

00:50:33.899 --> 00:50:39.979
learn and you don't make that mistake again. Whereas if you write all your functions, and then

00:50:40.620 --> 00:50:46.699
you're like, Okay, I'm now I'm going to write all the tests, writing the tests will teach you that

00:50:46.699 --> 00:50:52.620
some of your functions weren't really designed well. And then it just feels like a giant headache.

00:50:52.620 --> 00:51:00.300
